  "prompt": "How does blood flow from the heart to the brain?",
  "response": "Blood flow from the heart to the brain follows a specific pathway through the circulatory system. Here is a step-by-step outline of how this happens:\n\n1. **Left Ventricle**: Blood is pumped from the left ventricle of the heart into the aorta, the largest artery in the body.\n\n2. **Aorta**: The oxygen-rich blood travels through the aorta.\n\n3. **Common Carotid Arteries**: The aorta branches into the common carotid arteries. There are two common carotid arteries \u2013 one on the left side and one on the right.\n\n4. **External and Internal Carotid Arteries**: Each common carotid artery bifurcates into the external carotid artery, which supplies blood to the face and neck, and the internal carotid artery, which goes to the brain.\n\n5. **Internal Carotid Arteries and Vertebral Arteries**:\n    - **Internal Carotid Arteries**: These arteries enter the skull and provide major blood supply to the brain, particularly the anterior part, including parts of the frontal, temporal, and parietal lobes.\n    - **Vertebral Arteries**: Apart from the internal carotid arteries, blood can also reach the brain via the vertebral arteries, which branch off from the subclavian arteries and travel upward through the vertebrae of the spine. The two vertebral arteries merge to form the basilar artery.\n\n6. **Circle of Willis**: Both the internal carotid arteries and the basilar artery contribute to the Circle of Willis, a circular network of arteries located at the base of the brain. The Circle of Willis ensures consistent blood supply to the brain, even if one part of the pathway is blocked or narrowed.\n\nThe brain relies on a continuous supply of blood to function correctly, as blood delivers oxygen and nutrients while removing carbon dioxide and other waste products.",
